<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-189-172 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 260 779</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  April 1991 v10 n4 p21(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The Maverick and the Mark-1 eyeball. (the use of the infraredguided missile in the Gulf War)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrison, David C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The deaths of seven US servicemen in the early stages of the GulfWar at the hands of a infrared-guided missile fired from a US A-10attack plane, has raised some doubts about the ability of the&quot;smart&quot; missile to be used in military action in which friendlyand unfriendly forces are in close contact.andP;  The Maverick isreported to have worked without error against single enemy tanksin the desert.andP;  The missile is guided by scanning mirrors spinningat 3,600 revolutions-per-minute.andP;  The heat generated by the targetin front of the aircraft is concentrated onto a 16-elementinfrared detector.andP;  Critics of the missiles maintain that pickingout single enemy tanks in a desert is a far cry from isolatingindividual enemy targets in the middle of a ground skirmish, asthe deaths of the US servicemen in their Marine armored vehicledemonstrates.andP;  Some aircraft pilots maintain that the best way toensure a target is unfriendly is to verify with a visual sightingfirst.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryAircraftIraq-Kuwait Crisis, 1990-1991Maverick (Missile)Infrared Technology.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>